{"title_page": "Cristiana Oprea", "text_new": "{{short description|Romanian rally driver|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox racing driver\n| name              = Cristiana Oprea\n| image             =\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| nationality       = {{flagicon|ROU}}Romania\n| birth_name        = <!-- Only if different from name -->\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1992|03|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = \n| related to        = <!-- list of notable relatives with line breaks -->\n| current series    = European Rally Championship FIA ERC <br> DACIA Cup in the Romanian National Rally Championship\n| first year        = 2015\n| current team      = \n| car number        = \n| engine            = \n| crew chief        = \n| spotter           = <!-- Note: \"spotter\" and \"codriver\" share a field     -->\n| codriver          = Diana Ha\u021began\n| former teams      = \n| starts            = 23\n| wins              = \n| podiums           = 2\n| poles             = \n| fastest laps      = <!-- if known -->\n| best finish       = <!-- if a final championship placing has been recorded -->\n| year              = <!-- use piped link if season article exists -->\n| last finish       = \n| prev series       = <!-- previous series with line breaks -->\n| prev series years = \n| titles            = <!-- championship titles -->\n| title years       = \n| awards            = \n| award years       = \n| medaltemplates    = \n| updated           = \n}}\n'''Cristiana Oprea''' (born 11 March 1992) is a Romanian [[Rallying|rally]] driver. She is part of the very few ladies rally crews in Romania. Her career in rallying started in 2015, first as a codriver next to George Grigorescu, then as a driver in DACIA Cup, driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe.\n\nShe competes in the Romanian National Rally Championship and in the [[European Rally Championship]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiaerc.com/oprea-all-set-for-dream-step-up-to-erc-in-rome/|title=OPREA ALL SET FOR DREAM STEP UP TO ERC IN ROME|last=FIA ERC|website=www.fiaerc.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-23}}</ref> In July 2018 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first Romanian female rally crew in the last 50 years to compete in a foreign rally<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.agerpres.ro/sport/2018/07/17/auto-primul-echipaj-feminin-romanesc-din-ultimii-50-de-ani-la-un-raliu-in-afara-tarii--146346|title=Auto: Primul echipaj feminin rom\u00e2nesc din ultimii 50 de ani, la un raliu \u00een afara \u0163\u0103rii|last=AGERPRES|website=www.agerpres.ro|language=ro|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> (Rally Sliven, Bulgaria, a FIA [[European Rally Trophy]] event).\n\nIn July 2019 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first ladies crew to ever represent Romania in the FIA ERC European Rally Championship, at Rally di Roma Capitale, where they gained maximum points in the ERC Ladies Trophy standings driving a Peugeot 208 R2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiaerc.com/my-erc-debut-by-cristiana-oprea/|title=MY ERC DEBUT. BY CRISTIANA OPREA|last=FIA ERC|website=www.fiaerc.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-23}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Studies, career and motorsport debut ===\nOprea is a double graduate of the \"Ion Mincu\" University of Architecture and Urbanism in Bucharest. She studied Urban Planning (2010-2014) and Architecture (2011-2017), but she never worked in the field, wanting to follow her passion for cars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.femeia.ro/bani-cariera/cristiana-oprea-imi-doresc-sa-reprezint-romania-la-campionatul-european-de-raliuri|title=Cristiana Oprea: \u00cemi doresc s\u0103 reprezint Rom\u00e2nia la Campionatul European de Raliuri|last=-|date=2018-12-13|website=Femeia.ro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> In 2015 she was for a short while the PR of the Romanian Motorsport Federation, when she first took contact with the motorsport world. Her career in rallying started in 2015, first as a codriver next to George Grigorescu, Master of Sport and founder of the DACIA Cup series, then as a driver in DACIA Cup, driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe.\n\n==== Motorsport Excellence Centre Bucharest ====\nIn 2017, Oprea created the concept for a Motorsport Excellence Centre in Bucharest as an architecture graduation project.\n\n=== Racing career ===\nCristiana Oprea competed 2 full seasons, 2017 and 2018, in DACIA Cup,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cupadacia.ro/|title=Cupa DACIA|website=Cupa Dacia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> part of the Romanian National Rally Championship. Her rookie season was 2017, when she completed 7 events driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe with Ioana Stan as a codriver. They finished on 6th place out of 9 rookie crew and on 12th place out of 18 crews enlisted overall in DACIA Cup. In 2018 she finished on the 5th place overall in DACIA Cup, marking the best result of a woman driver since 2007, when Alina Bunica competed.\n\nOprea first stepped on a podium at the beginning of 2019 season at Arge\u0219 Rally, when together with codriver Diana Ha\u021began took second place overall<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cupadacia.ro/2019/05/07/cristi-sugar-vlad-colceriu-castiga-prima-etapa-cristiana-oprea-diana-hategan-scriu-istorie-in-cupa-dacia-la-raliul-argesului/|title=Cristi Sugar/Vlad Colceriu c\u00e2\u0219tig\u0103 prima etap\u0103, Cristiana Oprea/Diana Ha\u021began scriu istorie \u00een Cupa DACIA la Raliul Arge\u0219ului|date=2019-05-07|website=Cupa Dacia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> in DACIA Cup.\n\nIn July 2019 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first ladies crew to ever represent Romania in the FIA ERC European Rally Championship, at Rally di Roma Capitale, where they finished P8 in the highly competitive ERC3 class and gained maximum points in the ERC Ladies Trophy standings.\n\n=== Romanian Women in Motorsport platform ===\nOprea is the founder and administrator of \"Femei \u00een Motorsport\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://autostiri.ro/femei-motorsport-o-pagina-dedicata-promovarii-femeilor-implicate-automobilismul-si-motociclismul-din-romania/|title=Femei in motorsport, o pagina dedicata promov\u0103rii femeilor implicate \u00een automobilismul \u0219i motociclismul din Rom\u00e2nia|last=Strauti|first=Dan|date=2019-03-01|website=Autostiri.ro|language=ro-RO|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Romanian rally drivers]]\n[[Category:Female rally drivers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Romanian rally driver|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox racing driver\n| name              = Cristiana Oprea\n| image             =\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| nationality       = {{flagicon|ROU}}Romania\n| birth_name        = <!-- Only if different from name -->\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1992|03|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = \n| related to        = <!-- list of notable relatives with line breaks -->\n| current series    = European Rally Championship FIA ERC <br> DACIA Cup in the Romanian National Rally Championship\n| first year        = 2015\n| current team      = \n| car number        = \n| engine            = \n| crew chief        = \n| spotter           = <!-- Note: \"spotter\" and \"codriver\" share a field     -->\n| codriver          = Diana Ha\u021began\n| former teams      = \n| starts            = 23\n| wins              = \n| podiums           = 2\n| poles             = \n| fastest laps      = <!-- if known -->\n| best finish       = <!-- if a final championship placing has been recorded -->\n| year              = <!-- use piped link if season article exists -->\n| last finish       = \n| prev series       = <!-- previous series with line breaks -->\n| prev series years = \n| titles            = <!-- championship titles -->\n| title years       = \n| awards            = \n| award years       = \n| medaltemplates    = \n| updated           = \n}}\n'''Cristiana Oprea''' (born 11 March 1992) is a Romanian [[Rallying|rally]] driver. She is part of the very few all female rally crews in Romania. Her career in rallying started in 2015, first as a codriver next to George Grigorescu, then as a driver in DACIA Cup, driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe.\n\nShe competes in the Romanian National Rally Championship and in the [[European Rally Championship]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiaerc.com/oprea-all-set-for-dream-step-up-to-erc-in-rome/|title=OPREA ALL SET FOR DREAM STEP UP TO ERC IN ROME|last=FIA ERC|website=www.fiaerc.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-23}}</ref> In July 2018 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first Romanian female rally crew in the last 50 years to compete in a foreign rally<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.agerpres.ro/sport/2018/07/17/auto-primul-echipaj-feminin-romanesc-din-ultimii-50-de-ani-la-un-raliu-in-afara-tarii--146346|title=Auto: Primul echipaj feminin rom\u00e2nesc din ultimii 50 de ani, la un raliu \u00een afara \u0163\u0103rii|last=AGERPRES|website=www.agerpres.ro|language=ro|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> (Rally Sliven, Bulgaria, a FIA [[European Rally Trophy]] event).\n\nIn July 2019 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first ladies crew to ever represent Romania in the FIA ERC European Rally Championship, at Rally di Roma Capitale, where they gained maximum points in the ERC Ladies Trophy standings driving a Peugeot 208 R2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiaerc.com/my-erc-debut-by-cristiana-oprea/|title=MY ERC DEBUT. BY CRISTIANA OPREA|last=FIA ERC|website=www.fiaerc.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-23}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Studies, career and motorsport debut ===\nOprea is a double graduate of the \"Ion Mincu\" University of Architecture and Urbanism in Bucharest. She studied Urban Planning (2010-2014) and Architecture (2011-2017), but she never worked in the field, wanting to follow her passion for cars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.femeia.ro/bani-cariera/cristiana-oprea-imi-doresc-sa-reprezint-romania-la-campionatul-european-de-raliuri|title=Cristiana Oprea: \u00cemi doresc s\u0103 reprezint Rom\u00e2nia la Campionatul European de Raliuri|last=-|date=2018-12-13|website=Femeia.ro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> In 2015 she was for a short while the PR of the Romanian Motorsport Federation, when she first took contact with the motorsport world. Her career in rallying started in 2015, first as a codriver next to George Grigorescu, Master of Sport and founder of the DACIA Cup series, then as a driver in DACIA Cup, driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe.\n\n==== Motorsport Excellence Centre Bucharest ====\nIn 2017, Oprea created the concept for a Motorsport Excellence Centre in Bucharest as an architecture graduation project.\n\n=== Racing career ===\nCristiana Oprea competed 2 full seasons, 2017 and 2018, in DACIA Cup,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cupadacia.ro/|title=Cupa DACIA|website=Cupa Dacia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> part of the Romanian National Rally Championship. Her rookie season was 2017, when she completed 7 events driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe with Ioana Stan as a codriver. They finished on 6th place out of 9 rookie crew and on 12th place out of 18 crews enlisted overall in DACIA Cup. In 2018 she finished on the 5th place overall in DACIA Cup, marking the best result of a woman driver since 2007, when Alina Bunica competed.\n\nOprea first stepped on a podium at the beginning of 2019 season at Arge\u0219 Rally, when together with codriver Diana Ha\u021began took second place overall<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cupadacia.ro/2019/05/07/cristi-sugar-vlad-colceriu-castiga-prima-etapa-cristiana-oprea-diana-hategan-scriu-istorie-in-cupa-dacia-la-raliul-argesului/|title=Cristi Sugar/Vlad Colceriu c\u00e2\u0219tig\u0103 prima etap\u0103, Cristiana Oprea/Diana Ha\u021began scriu istorie \u00een Cupa DACIA la Raliul Arge\u0219ului|date=2019-05-07|website=Cupa Dacia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> in DACIA Cup.\n\nIn July 2019 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first ladies crew to ever represent Romania in the FIA ERC European Rally Championship, at Rally di Roma Capitale, where they finished P8 in the highly competitive ERC3 class and gained maximum points in the ERC Ladies Trophy standings.\n\n=== Romanian Women in Motorsport platform ===\nOprea is the founder and administrator of \"Femei \u00een Motorsport\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://autostiri.ro/femei-motorsport-o-pagina-dedicata-promovarii-femeilor-implicate-automobilismul-si-motociclismul-din-romania/|title=Femei in motorsport, o pagina dedicata promov\u0103rii femeilor implicate \u00een automobilismul \u0219i motociclismul din Rom\u00e2nia|last=Strauti|first=Dan|date=2019-03-01|website=Autostiri.ro|language=ro-RO|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Romanian rally drivers]]\n[[Category:Female rally drivers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "AutomobilismRO", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cristiana_Oprea"}
{"title_page": "Saudi Vision 2030", "text_new": "{{Copy edit|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox government agency\n| agency_name = Saudi Vision 2030\n| nativename = '' \u0631\u0624\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629 2030''\n| type = Development programme\n| seal = \n| logo = Saudi Vision 2030 logo.svg\n| logo_width = 200px\n| logo_caption = The official logo of the project.\n| formed = {{Start date and age|2016|04|25|df=yes}}\n| jurisdiction = [[Government of Saudi Arabia]]\n| minister1_name = [[Mohammad bin Salman]]\n| minister1_pfo = [[Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia]]\n| chief1_name = \n| chief1_position = \n| chief2_name = \n| chief2_position = \n| chief3_name = \n| chief3_position = \n| chief4_name = \n| chief4_position = \n| chief5_name = \n| motto = Saudi Arabia the heart of the Arab and Islamic worlds, the investment powerhouse, and the hub connecting three continents\n| employees = \n| budget = \n| agency_type = Development programme\n| chief5_position = \n| chief6_name = \n| chief6_position = \n| chief7_name = \n| chief7_position = \n| chief8_name = \n| chief8_position = \n| chief9_name = \n| chief9_position = \n| parent_department = \n| keydocument1 = '''Saudi Vision 2030'''\n* [http://vision2030.gov.sa/download/file/fid/417 English]\n* [http://vision2030.gov.sa/download/file/fid/422 Arabic]\n| website = {{URL|http://vision2030.gov.sa/}}\n}}\n{{Politics of Saudi Arabia}}\n\n'''Saudi Vision 2030''' ({{lang-ar|\u0631\u0624\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629 2030}}) is a strategic framework to reduce [[Saudi Arabia]]'s dependence on [[Saudi oil|oil]], diversify its [[economy of Saudi Arabia|economy]], and develop public service sectors such as health, [[education in Saudi Arabia|education]], infrastructure, recreation and [[tourism in Saudi Arabia|tourism]]. Key strategic goals include reinforcing economic and investment activities, increasing non-oil industry trade between countries and to promote a softer and secular image of the Kingdom . It also consists of increasing government spending on the [[Military of Saudi Arabia|military]], manufacturing equipment and ammunition.\n\nThe first details were announced on 25 April 2016 by Crown Prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Marwa Rashad |title=Saudis await Prince's vision of future with hope and concern |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-plan-idUSKCN0XL0B2 |newspaper=Reuters |date=24 April 2016 |access-date= 24 April 2016}}</ref> The Council of Ministers has tasked the [[Council of Economic and Development Affairs (Saudi Arabia)|Council of Economic and Development Affairs]] (CEDA) with identifying and monitoring the mechanisms and measures crucial for the implementation of \"Saudi Arabia\u2019s Vision 2030\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://vision2030.gov.sa/sites/default/files/NTP_En.pdf |title=National Transformation Program 2020 |last= |first= |date= |website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of Vision 2030, foreign investments in the country rose in 2018 by 110% representing double the previous year according to the [[Ministry of Economy and Planning|minister of economy and planning]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-budget-energy-industry-idUKKBN1OI0QU|title=Foreign investment in Saudi Arabia more than doubled in 2018: minister|date=2018-12-19|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-01-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nOil comprises 30-40 percent of the real [[GDP]] of Saudi Arabia, not including the proportion of the economy that is also dependent on the oil distribution. Decreasing this dependence on oil resources has been one of the goals of the government since the 1970s. However, the implementation of this goal has been rather unstable and largely dependent on the prices of oil. The core priority is to be able to develop more alternative sources of revenue for the government, such as taxes, fees and income from the sovereign wealth fund.<ref name=\":0\" /> Another major aspect is to lower the dependency of the citizens of the country on public spending such as spending on subsidies, higher salaries and to increase the portion of the economy contributed by the private sector to provide more employment opportunities and to provide growth in the GDP.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web |url=http://vision2030.gov.sa/sites/default/files/NTP_En.pdf |title=Vision 2030 |last= |first= |date= |website=|access-date=}}</ref> The goals in the Saudi vision 2030 could be compared with other development plans in the Middle East, see for example the [[Kuwait Vision 2035]], [[UAE vision 2021|UAE Vision]] and [[Qatar National Vision 2030]].\n\nThe vision has 3 main pillars: the status of the country as the \"heart of the Arab and Islamic worlds\"; the determination to become a global investment powerhouse; and finally to transform the country's location into a hub connecting the 3 continents (Asia, Europe, Africa).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/perspective/features/2016/04/26/Full-text-of-Saudi-Arabia-s-Vision-2030.html |title=Full-text-of-Saudi-Arabia-s-Vision-2030 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429180619/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/perspective/features/2016/04/26/Full-text-of-Saudi-Arabia-s-Vision-2030.html|archive-date=2016-04-29|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe plan is supervised by a group of people employed under the National Center for Performance Measurement, the Delivery Unit, and the Project Management Office of the Council of Economic and Development Affairs. The National Transformation Program was designed and launched in 2016 across 24 government bodies to enhance the economic and development center.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nSaudi Arabia Vision 2030 lays out targets for diversification and improving competitiveness. It is built around three main themes which set out specific objectives that are to be achieved by the year 2030.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/perspective/features/2016/04/26/Full-text-of-Saudi-Arabia-s-Vision-2030.html |title=Full text of Saudi Arabia\u2019s Vision 2030 |website=english.alarabiya.net |language=en|access-date=2017-12-13}}</ref>\n# A vibrant society: urbanism, culture and entertainment, sports, Umrah, UNESCO heritage sites, life expectancy.\n# A thriving economy: Employment, women in the workforce, international competitiveness, Public Investment Fund, Foreign direct investment, private sector, non-oil exports.\n# An ambitious nation: Non-oil revenues, government effectiveness, and e-government, household savings and income, non-profits and volunteering.\n\n== Projects and initiatives ==\nThe [[Public Investment Fund of Saudi Arabia|PIF]] annually organizes an investment forum, the [[Future Investment Initiative]] or \"Davos in the Desert\" in context of Saudi Vision 2030 in Riyadh. However, amid the rising controversy and escalating tensions due to Saudi's involvement in [[Jamal Khashoggi]]\u2019s disappearance, many companies\u2019 CEOs have backed out of the conference. [[Google Cloud Platform|Google Cloud]], [[KKR & Co. L.P.]], [[Ford Motor Company|Ford Motor]], [[JPMorgan Chase]], [[BlackRock]], [[Uber]] and [[The Blackstone Group]] all withdrew their CEO/Chairman's names from the summit that was held on 23 October 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/finance-ceos-pull-out-of-saudi-davos-in-the-desert-over-khashoggi-risking-lucrative-role-in-kingdoms-economic-reforms/2018/10/15/b10afea4-d0b8-11e8-b2d2-f397227b43f0_story.html?noredirect=on|title=Finance CEOs pull out of Saudi \u2018Davos in the Desert\u2019 over Khashoggi, risking lucrative role in kingdom\u2019s economic reforms|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> Major media houses including [[CNN]], [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]], [[CNBC]], the [[New York Times]], [[Fox Business Network]], the [[Financial Times]], the [[Los Angeles Times]] and [[Huffington Post]] also withdrew as partners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/11/media/saudi-conference-media-sponsors-khashoggi/index.html|title=Media sponsors drop out of Saudi conference after journalist goes missing|publisher=CNN|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== National Transformation Program ===\nOn 7 June 2016, the Saudi Council of Ministers approved the National Transformation Program which sets out the goals and targets to be achieved by the Kingdom by 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/business/economy/2017/05/01/Saudi-Arabia-sets-out-10-programs-to-achieve-the-Vision-2030.html |title=Saudi Arabia sets out 10 programs to achieve Vision 2030 |website=Alarabiya.net |date=1 May 2017 |accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref> It is the first out of three phases each lasting for five years. Each phase will contribute towards achieving a certain number of goals and targets that will eventually help the Kingdom in reaching the ultimate goals of Vision 2030. In addition, to assist the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia to finance all the projects to be developed and facilitate the process of achieving the goals and targets of Vision 2030, Crown Prince Mohammad bin Salman announced, in January 2016, that an [[Initial public offering|IPO]] of [[Saudi Aramco|Saudi ARAMCO]] is going to take place. However, only 5% of the company will be offered on the stock market.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21685529-biggest-oil-all-saudi-arabia-considering-ipo-aramco-probably |title=Saudi Arabia is considering an IPO of Aramco, probably the world\u2019s most valuable company |website=The Economist|access-date=2017-12-13}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Aramco released its financial statements revealing a net income of $111.1 billion in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-aramco-fitch/aramcos-10-billion-plus-bond-plan-shows-profits-put-top-earner-apple-in-shade-idUSKCN1RD15E|title=Aramco's $10 billion-plus bond plan shows profits put top earner Apple in shade|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=31 March 2019}}</ref> In June 2019, [[Financial Times]] reported that Aramco is striving to separate its association with the ministry, ahead of its potential listing. The company has been paying ministry-related expenses, which according to an unnamed person have been kept hidden by Aramco. The report revealed that [[Khalid A. Al-Falih|Khalid Al-Falih]] has been using the company's revenues for his expenses, which are either directly related to Aramco or are diplomatic. However, Falih's ally stated that the chairman's policies have brought in greater revenues for the firm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/96a6fc26-8b92-11e9-a24d-b42f641eca37|title=Saudi Aramco battles oil ministry over use of company funds|publisher=Financial Times|accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Red Sea luxury resort project ===\nA beach resort is proposed to be built on the [[Red Sea]] between the towns of [[Umluj]] and [[Al-Wajh]] in the northern section of the [[Hejaz]]i coast.<ref name = \"resort\">{{cite news |url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1138636/columns |title=Red Sea resort an essential element of Saudi Vision 2030 |date=2 August 2017}}</ref> The resort project will involve, \"50 islands and 34,000 square kilometers in a global upmarket tourism and leisure mega-development\"<ref name = \"resort\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/blog/2017/8/2/bikini-clad-women-in-saudi-arabia-yes-really |title=Bikini-clad women in Saudi Arabia? Yes, really... |date=2 August 2017}}</ref> and will be, \"governed by laws on par with international standards.\" The resort will allow women to wear [[bikinis]] in the pool and beach areas.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2017/08/04/saudi-arabia-allow-women-wear-bikinis-new-beach-resort/538407001/ |title=Saudi Arabia to allow women in bikinis at new beach resort |date=4 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2017/08/05/Women-to-be-allowed-to-wear-bikinis-at-Saudi-Arabia-beach-resort/7121501939370/ |title=Women to be allowed to wear bikinis at Saudi Arabia beach resort |date=5 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe two massive tourism projects along the Red Sea planned by the Saudi government were to be run under the directorship of [[Richard Branson]]. On 11 October 2018, Branson stated that he is suspending his advisory role for the two projects amidst the [[Jamal Khashoggi]] murder.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.virgin.com/richard-branson/my-statement-kingdom-saudi-arabia|title=My Statement on the Kingdom of audi Arabia|accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref> Branson also suspended his talks with the Saudi government about investment in his [[Virgin Galactic]] venture. He said he had \"high hopes for the current government in the Kingdom and its leader Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman\u2026the disappearance of journalist Jamal Khashoggi, if proved true, would clearly change the ability of any of us in the West to do business with the Saudi Government.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2018/oct/11/sir-richard-branson-suspends-saudi-business-talks-over-khashoggi-affair|title=Sir Richard Branson suspends Saudi business talks over Khashoggi affair|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Entertainment sector ===\nIn May 2016, a [[General Authority for Entertainment (Saudi Arabia)|General Authority for Entertainment]] was announced by royal decree, into which over $2 billion have been invested. In Riyadh, the first public live music concert in over 25 years was held in May 2017, which featured American [[country music]]ian [[Toby Keith]] and Saudi singer [[Rabeh Sager]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21722829-puritanical-kingdom-experiments-entertainment-saudi-arabia-allows |title=Saudi Arabia allows concerts\u2014even country music |website=Economist.com |date=1 June 2017 |accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/therecord/2017/05/22/529500923/how-did-toby-keith-get-to-do-a-concert-in-saudi-arabia |title=How Did Toby Keith Get To Do A Concert In Saudi Arabia? |website=Npr.org |date=22 May 2017 |author=Anastasia Tsioulcas |accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref> In April 2017, the government announced a large sports, culture and entertainment complex, of {{convert|334|km2|ha|lk=in}} at Al-Qidiya, south-west of [[Riyadh]]. The project will include a [[Six Flags]] theme park, due to open in 2022.<ref name=\"sixflags\">{{Cite web |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/life-style/travel-and-tourism/2017/04/08/Saudi-Arabia-plans-on-building-its-largest-cultural-sports-and-recreation-city.html |title=Prince Mohammed bin Salman announces Saudi plans for largest entertainment city |website=english.alarabiya.net |language=en|access-date=2017-12-13}}</ref>\n\nAs a component of Vision 2030 there was a celebration of the 87th anniversary of the Saudi founding with concerts and performances, with women for the first time being allowed into the [[King Fahd International Stadium]] in Riyadh.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://zeenews.india.com/world/women-allowed-into-stadium-as-saudi-arabia-promotes-national-pride-part-of-reform-push-2044950.html |title=Women allowed into stadium as Saudi Arabia promotes national pride, part of reform push |date=23 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 5, 2018, the [[General Sports Authority]] announced a 10-year partnership with American [[professional wrestling]] promoter [[WWE|World Wrestling Entertainment]] (WWE) to hold annual [[pay-per-view]] events in Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"GRR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wwe.com/worldwide/article/saudi-arabia-to-host-greatest-royal-rumble-april-2018 |title=Saudi Arabia to host the Greatest Royal Rumble |work=[[WWE]] |author=WWE.com staff |date=March 5, 2018 |accessdate=March 7, 2018}}</ref> The first event, [[Greatest Royal Rumble]], was held 27 April 2018 at [[King Abdullah Sports City]] in [[Jeddah]].<ref name=\"GRR\" /> Due to restrictions on women's rights, WWE's female performers are not featured in these events. An exception to this occurred at [[Crown Jewel (2019)|Crown Jewel]] on 31 October 2019, which featured [[Lacey Evans]] and [[Natalya Neidhart|Natalya]] in the first women's professional wrestling match to be held in Saudi Arabia. In observation of conservative dress, they both wore black leggings and T-shirts over bodysuits instead of their normal ring attire.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://mirrorherald.com/crown-jewel-in-saudi-hosted-women-players-for-first-time/|title=Reforms Under Veil: Saudi\u2019s First Women Wrestling Battled in Bodysuits|accessdate=1 February 2020|website=Mirror Herald}}</ref>\n\nSaudi Arabia lifted its 35-year moratorium on the construction of new [[movie theater]]s in the country, with the first (under the ownership of [[AMC Theatres]]) opened on 18 April 2018 in [[Riyadh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/04/18/media/saudi-arabia-movies-black-panther-amc/index.html|title='Black Panther' comes to Saudi Arabia as movie theater ban ends|last1=Petroff|first1=Alanna|date=18 April 2018|website=CNN.com|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/amc-proceeding-plan-build-movie-theaters-saudi-arabia-1199362|title=AMC Proceeding With Plan to Build Movie Theaters in Saudi Arabia|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, the MDL Beast [[music festival]] was held in Riyadh, attracting 200,000 visitors over three days, and featuring acts such as [[Afrojack]], [[David Guetta]], [[Monsta X]] [[R3hab]], and [[J Balvin]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/music/i-don-t-have-to-leave-saudi-for-fun-anymore-mdl-beast-represents-a-paradigm-shift-in-the-kingdom-1.954878|title='I don't have to leave Saudi for fun anymore': MDL Beast represents a 'paradigm shift' in the kingdom|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Saudi Arabia unveiled its plans to build a new racing circuit in [[Al-Qiddiya|Qiddiya]], designed by former [[Formula One]] driver [[Alexander Wurz]], with a goal for it to host F1 or [[MotoGP]] events as early as 2023.<ref name=\"BBCJan20\">{{cite news|author=Andrew Benson|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/51137520|title=Formula 1: Saudi Arabia unveils plans for race in 2023|date=17 January 2020|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Women's rights ===\nIn January 2013, women were announced as members of the nation's [[Consultative Assembly of Saudi Arabia|Consultative Assembly]]. In 2015, they were allowed to run for office in municipal elections.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2013/01/11/saudi-king-grants-women-seats-on-advisory-council-for-1st-time.html |title=Saudi king grants women seats on advisory council for 1st time |website=Foxnews.com |date=11 January 2013 |accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2017, Saudi state schools announced offering physical education classes to both boys and girls starting in the fall of 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/07/13/saudi-arabia-state-schools-allow-girls-sports |title=Saudi Arabia: State Schools to Allow Girls\u2019 Sports |website=Hrw.org |date=13 July 2017 |accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref> Later that same year, the state announced allowing men and women to attend sports events, including inside sports stadiums.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/30/saudi-arabia-to-allow-women-into-sports-stadiums-as-reform-push-intensifies |title=Saudi Arabia to allow women into sports stadiums as reform push intensifies |website=Theguardian.com |date=30 October 2017 |accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref> On September 26, 2017, a royal decree granted women the right to drive vehicles, a move which would take effect in June 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/26/world/middleeast/saudi-arabia-women-drive.html |title=Saudi Arabia Agrees to Let Women Drive |website=Nytimes.com |date=26 September 2017 |author=Ben Hubbard |accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhile a few relaxations were suggested and implemented by the government for the welfare of women, more progress still needs to be made. As many women activists have been held and criminalized since 2015, without allowing access to a lawyer. The case of [[Israa al-Ghomgham]] came into light after she and her husband were arrested in December 2015 for calling the release of political prisoners and an end to anti-Shia government discrimination.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/saudi-arabia-israa-alghomgham-execution-womens-rights-political-activist-qatif-a8501411.html|title=Saudi Arabia plans to execute first female political activist|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref> Saudi prosecutors are seeking death penalty for Ghomgham.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/aug/22/saudi-arabia-seeks-its-first-death-penalty-against-a-female-human-rights-activist|title=Saudi Arabia seeks death penalty against female human rights activist|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the government based web application [[Absher (application)|Absher]] gained media attention and was criticized for tracking the movement of the women of the kingdom. The app, which promotes a male guardianship system, allows men to manage women's lives digitally by specifying when and from where a woman can travel. The app also sends alerts to men's phones in case a woman uses her passport at the border.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisisinsider.com/absher-saudi-website-men-control-women-stop-escape-2019-1|title=Saudi Arabia runs a huge, sinister online database of women that men use to track them and stop them from running away|publisher=The Insider|accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref> The European Parliament, US Senator and US Representatives condemned the app and urged the kingdom to abolish its male guardianship system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-eu-saudi-women/eu-lawmakers-urge-saudi-arabia-to-end-womens-guardianship-system-idUKKCN1Q327T|title=EU lawmakers urge Saudi Arabia to end women's guardianship system|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisisinsider.com/absher-saudi-arabia-defends-app-investigated-by-apple-google-2019-2|title=Saudi Arabia tried to justify its app that lets men control where women travel amid a firestorm of criticism| publisher=The Insider|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Tourism Visa ===\nIn compliance with Saudi vision 2030, Saudi Arabia formally announced on 27 September 2019 the issuance of the tourist visa allowing visitors from 49 countries to visit the country up to 90 days for a fee of $80. The visa can be either obtained online (eVisa) or on arrival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.visitsaudi.com/en/about-evisa.html|title=Welcome to Arabia - About the Tourism Visa |last=|first= |date= |website=visitsaudi.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Other projects ===\nSome of the other major projects to be developed are listed in the table below:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Some of the projects to be developed as a part of Vision 2030\n!Project Name\n!Location\n!Total Area (km\u00b2)\n!Date of Announcement\n!Expected Finish Date\n!Cost\n|-\n!New Taif Project<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/518430/SAUDI-ARABIA/Taif-projects |title=King inaugurates SR11bn New Taif projects |date=2017-10-01 |work=Saudigazette|access-date=2017-12-13 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n|[[Taif]]\n|1250\n|1 March 2017\n|2020\n|3 Billion Dollars\n|-\n!Diriyah Gate Project<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1421416/saudi-arabia|title=Ad Diriyah a \u2018jewel\u2019 of Saudi Arabia, its revival key to Kingdom\u2019s future, says project chief|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n| [[Diriyah]]\n| 1.5\n|20 July 2017\n|2030\n|Unknown\n|-\n![[Al-Qiddiya|Al-Qiddiya Project]]<ref name=\"sixflags\"/>\n|Al-Qiddiya, south-west of [[Riyadh]]\n|334\n|8 April 2017\n|2022\n|2.7 Billion Dollars\n|-\n!Al-Faisaliah project<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.argaam.com/en/article/articledetail/id/497359 |title=Al-Faisaliah project to be finalized by 2050, says Makkah governor |date=26 July 2017 |work=Argaam.com|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1165351/saudi-arabia|title=Makkah\u2019s Al-Faisaliah project to be unveiled at Jeddah property show|date=22 September 2017|website=Arab News|language=en-US|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref> \n|West of [[Makkah]] \n|2,450 \n|26 July 2017\n|First Phase will be completed by the end of 2020\n|Unknown\n|-\n!Downtown Jeddah<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-09-27/saudi-fund-to-develop-jeddah-downtown-with-4-8-billion-project |title=Saudi Fund to Develop Jeddah Downtown With $4.8 Billion Project |work=Bloomberg.com |access-date=2017-12-13 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005075051/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-09-27/saudi-fund-to-develop-jeddah-downtown-with-4-8-billion-project |archivedate=2017-10-05 }}</ref>\n|[[Jeddah]]\n|5.2\n|27 September 2017\n|First phase will be completed by the end of 2022\n|4.8 Billion Dollars\n|-\n![[NEOM]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-24/saudi-arabia-to-build-new-mega-city-on-country-s-north-coast |title=Saudi Arabia Just Announced Plans to Build a Mega City That Will Cost $500 Billion |date=2017-10-24 |work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2017-12-13}}</ref>\n|Northwest of Saudi Arabia \n|26,500\n|24 October 2017\n|First Phase will be completed by the end of 2025\n|500 Billion Dollars\n|-\n!The Renewable Energy Project<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-softbank-group-solar/softbank-says-it-is-working-with-saudi-pif-on-solar-power-project-idUSKCN1MC28T|title=Softbank says it is working with Saudi PIF on solar power project|website=Reuters.com|language=en|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n| Multiple Locations\n| Unknown\n|27 March 2018\n|2030\n|200 Billion\n|-\n![[Amaala|Amaala Project]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimdobson/2018/12/26/saudi-arabia-unveils-plans-to-create-massive-red-sea-wellness-destinations/#3b97aa55dfb6 |title=Saudi Arabia Unveils Plans To Create Massive Red Sea Wellness Destinations |date=26 December 2018 |work=Forbes.com|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n|Along the [[Red Sea]] \n|3,800\n|26 September 2018\n|First Phase will be completed by the end of 2020\n|Unknown\n|-\n![[King Salman Energy Park]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saudiaramco.com:443/en/News-Media/News/2018/King%20Salman%20Energy%20Park|title=King Salman Energy Park: Saudi Aramco builds a sustainable global energy hub from the ground up - Saudi Aramco|website=saudiaramco.com|language=en|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n|Between [[Dammam]] and [[Al-Ahsa Governorate|Al-Ahsa]]\n|50\n|5 December 2018\n|First Phase will be completed by the end of 2021\n|1.6 Billion\n|-\n![[Al-`Ula#Al-Ula vision|Al-Ula Vision]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cic.org.sa/2019/02/royal-commission-for-alula-hosts-launching-the-vision-for-alula/|title=Royal Commission for AlUla hosts \u2018Launching the Vision for AlUla\u2019|website=The Saudi Center for International Communication|language=en|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/558885/SAUDI-ARABIA/Al-Ula-Vision-KSA-gift-to-world|title='Al Ula Vision... Saudi Arabia gift to world'|date=2019-02-11|website=Saudigazette|language=English|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref>\n| [[Al-`Ula]]\n| 22500\n|11 February 2019\n|2030\n|Unknown\n|-\n![[King Salman Park]], Sports Boulevard, Green Riyadh and Riyadh Art<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saudiaramco.com:443/en/News-Media/News/2018/King%20Salman%20Energy%20Park|title=King Salman Launches $23 Bln Wellbeing Projects in Riyadh|website=Asharq Al-Awsat|language=en|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saudiaramco.com:443/en/News-Media/News/2018/King%20Salman%20Energy%20Park|title=King Salman Announces $23 Billion for Four Entertainment Projects Including the \u2018World\u2019s Biggest Park\u2019 in Riyadh|website=Saudi-US Trade Group|language=en|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n| [[Riyadh]]\n| +149\n|19 March 2019\n|Unknown\n|23 Billion\n|-\n![[Great Mosque of Mecca]]<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/528131|title=Expansion and redevelopment define Saudi Arabia construction|date=2018-02-11|website=Saudigazette|language=English|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n|[[Mecca]]\n|250,000 \n|2017\n|mid-2018\n|21.3 Billion Dollars\n|-\n!Mall of Saudi<ref name=\":3\" />\n|[[Riyadh]]\n|8666,000\n|2017\n|2022\n|3.2 Billion Dollars\n|-\n!New Jeddah Downtown \u2013 Phase 1<ref name=\":3\" />\n|[[Jeddah]]\n|unknown\n|2017\n|unknown\n|2 Billion Dollars\n|-\n|}\n\n== Implementation ==\n=== Vision Realization Programs ===\nTo achieve the strategic goals and targets of vision 2030, thirteen programs called Vision Realization Programs (VRPs) were established. The VRPs were presented by [[Council of Economic and Development Affairs (Saudi Arabia)|Council of Economic and Development Affairs]] (CEDA) on Monday 24 April 2017. The VRPs are as follows:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vision2030.gov.sa/en/programs|title=Programs {{!}} Saudi Vision 2030|website=vision2030.gov.sa|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref>\n\n#[[Quality of Life Program 2020|Quality of Life Program]].\n# Financial Sector Development Program.\n# Housing Program.\n# Fiscal Balance Program.\n#[[National Transformation Program 2020 (Saudi Arabia)|National Transformation Program]].\n#[[Public Investment Fund of Saudi Arabia|Public Investment Fund Program]].\n# Privatization Program.\n# National Companies Promotion Program.\n# National Industrial Development and Logistics Program.\n# Strategic Partnerships Program.\n# Hajj and Umrah Program.\n# Human Capital Development Program.\n# Saudi Character Enrichment Program.\n\n=== Supervision ===\nThe plan is supervised by Crown Prince Mohammad bin Salman. Three levels ensure the application of the plan:\n* Overall, Vision 2030's directions and decision-making roles lie within a Council of Ministers and a [[Council of Economic and Development Affairs (Saudi Arabia)|Council of Economic and Development Affairs]] (CEDA).\n* CEDA's director, as well as the managers of the first 12 Vision Realization Programs, ensure the following-up of the plan on the five-year level.\n* Annually, each entity concerned in the 2030 Vision is individually responsible for its budget and objectives.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n=== Government entities reconstruction ===\nTo achieve the strategic objectives of Vision 2030, new government entities were created and existing entities were reconstructed and/or merged.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vision2030.gov.sa/download/file/fid/1319|title=KSA Vision 2030 Strategic Objectives and Vision Realization Programs|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! New entity\n! Reconstructed and/or merged from previous entity\n! Previous entity\n|-\n|[[Council of Economic and Development Affairs (Saudi Arabia)|Council of Economic and Development Affairs]] (CEDA) PMO\n| No\n| \n|-\n|Delivery Unit (DU)\n| No\n|\n|-\n|National Center for Performance Management (Adaa)\n| No\n|\n|-\n|Corporate Communication Unit at CEDA (CCU) \n| No\n|\n|-\n|General Authority for Culture (GAC)\n| No\n|\n|-\n|[[General Authority for Entertainment (Saudi Arabia)|General Authority for Entertainment]] of (GEA)\n| No\n|\n|-\n|Strategic Management Committee and Strategic Management Office (SMO)\n| No\n|\n|-\n|[[Ministry of Commerce and Investment (Saudi Arabia)|Ministry of Commerce and Investment]]\n| Yes\n|Ministry of Commerce and Industry\n|-\n|Ministry of Labor Ministry of Labor and Social Development\n| Yes\n|Ministry of Social Affairs\n|-\n|Ministry of Energy, Industry and Mineral Resources\n| Yes\n|Ministry of Petroleum and Mineral Resources and\n|-\n|Ministry of Environment, Water and Agriculture\n|\n|Ministry of Water and Electricity and Ministry of Agriculture\n|-\n|[[Ministry of Hajj and Umrah]]\n| Yes\n|Ministry of [[Hajj]]\n|-\n|Public Education Evaluation Commission\n| Yes\n|Education Evaluation Commission\n|}\n\n== Critical reactions ==\nThe [[IMF]]'s country report on Saudi Arabia, launched a few months following the announcement of Vision 2030, explained that the fiscal deficit in the Saudi economy would indeed continue to narrow in 2016. It also claimed that recent, major government deposits at the [[Saudi Arabian Monetary Authority]] (SAMA) acted as policy buffers to smooth the transition that the plan is leading.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/scr/2016/cr16326.pdf |title=IMF Country Report No. 16/326 |website=Imf.org |date=October 2016 |accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref> In 2016 the IMF publicly warned that Saudi Arabia risks having no more foreign reserve currency within a 5-year period.<ref name=\"ody\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theodysseyonline.com/saudi-arabias-vision-2030-is-going-to-fail |title=Saudi Arabia\u2019s Vision 2030 Is Going To Fail |website=Theodysseyonline.com |date=16 May 2016 |author=Ian Leclecr |accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref> In 2017, it projected that SAMA's net foreign assets would continue to decline, though remaining at a \"comfortable level\". It expects that the fiscal deficit will continue to improve over the coming years, also noting that non-performing loans remained low, despite a slight increase to 1.4 percent in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imf.org/en/News/Articles/2017/07/21/pr17292-imf-executive-board-concludes-2017-article-iv-consultation-with-saudi-arabia |title=IMF Executive Board Concludes 2017 Article IV Consultation with Saudi Arabia |website=Imf.org |date=21 July 2017 |accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nOver 300 specific targets have been announced across 25 government entities via the National Transformation Plan document to reach these objectives by 2020. The National Transformation Plan brings over 150 expected initial public offerings. However, reports noted the \"key person dependency\" of the Vision and the NTP, with regards to Crown Prince Mohammad bin Salman.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gib.com/sites/default/files/ntp_ebook_-_final_12_-_low-res_0_0.pdf |title=Assessment of the National Transformation Program (NTP) |website=Gib.com |date=2016 |accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref> Other criticisms have been regarding the lack of information about the detailed plans to accompany the intended transformation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.bath.ac.uk/iprblog/2017/08/10/the-uncertain-vision-saudi-arabia-and-vision-2030/ |title=Looking to the Future: Saudi Arabia and Vision 2030 |website=Bath.ac.uk |date=10 August 2017 |accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nCertain journalists speculated that the plan's goals were overly ambitious, and noted that non-oil growth so far was insufficient and would threaten the plan's successful implementation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oilprice.com/Energy/Energy-General/How-Realistic-Is-Saudi-Arabias-2-Trillion-Sovereign-Wealth-Fund.html |title=How Realistic Is Saudi Arabia\u2019s $2 Trillion Sovereign Wealth Fund? |website=Oilprice.com |date=7 April 2017 |author=Rakesh Upadhyay |accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-01/saudi-non-oil-growth-is-stagnating-even-with-2030-vision-chart |title=Saudi Non-Oil Growth Is Stagnating Even With 2030 Vision: Chart |website=Bloomberg.com |date=1 October 2017 |author=Vivian Nereim |accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref> One report felt that despite the national plan's overall forward-thinking direction, \"political reform appears to be absent from the policy agenda\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chathamhouse.org/sites/files/chathamhouse/publications/research/2017-07-20-vision-2030-saudi-kinninmont.pdf |title=Vision 2030 and Saudi Arabia\u2019s Social Contract |website=Chathamhouse.org |date=July 2017 |author=Jane Kinninmont |accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nReactions were mixed following the announcement that Saudi Arabia would lift the driving ban on women.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/09/saudi-women-driving-ban-lifted-euphoria-sarcasm-170927053659253.html |title=Saudi women driving ban lifted: Euphoria and sarcasm |website=Aljazeera.com |date=27 September 2017 |accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref> Similarly to the overarching Vision 2030, some understood the announcement via royal decree as a reaction to outside pressure, while others applauded the move.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/posteverything/wp/2017/09/28/yes-letting-women-in-saudi-arabia-drive-is-a-baby-step-but-we-shouldnt-laugh-at-it/ |title=Yes, letting women in Saudi Arabia drive is a baby step. But we shouldn\u2019t laugh at it |website=Washinpost.com |date=28 September 2017 |author=Eman Quotah |accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a research paper written by Jane Kinninmont for the Middle East and North Africa Programme, from the structural disadvantages of the country such as weak institutions, inefficient bureaucracy and significant gaps between the labor force required by the labor market and the current educational system hinder some of the growth prospects of the country. Rebalancing the job market in the private sector will also prove to be a challenge since it is currently majority staffed by expatriates. One of the difficulties is that the private sector has lower paying salaries and expats are easier to hire and fire. Currently twice as many Saudi nationals work in the public sector than in the private sector. The challenge lies in getting a larger portion of the nationals to accept lower paying jobs that could require higher working hours than that of the public sector. Another aspect to be considered is moving the private sector away from the business activities that require very low-cost labor.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.chathamhouse.org/sites/files/chathamhouse/publications/research/2017-07-20-vision-2030-saudi-kinninmont.pdf |title=Vision 2030 and Saudi Arabia\u2019s Social Contract Austerity and Transformation |last= |first= |date= |website=Chathamhouse|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Hilal Khashan from the American conservative think tank [[Middle East Forum]], to have the 2030 plan succeed ignoring the relationship between economic and political development is no longer a viable option, the developments required to increase the GDP as planned will encourage the breakage of the tribal system taking place. Another aspect is the \"zero tolerance to corruption\" that may be very difficult to achieve with a \"society where family, tribal, and regional ties are stronger than the nebulous conception of state identity\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal |last=Khashan |first=Hilal |date=2017-01-01 |title=Saudi Arabia's Flawed \"Vision 2030\" |url=http://www.meforum.org/6397/saudi-arabia-flawed-vision-2030 |journal=Middle East Quarterly |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe hosting of sporting events in Saudi Arabia under the strategy have been described as attempts to [[Sportswashing|sportswash]] the country's human rights record.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Zidan|first=Karim|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/sep/02/sportswashing-saudi-arabia-sports-mohammed-bin-salman|title=Sportswashing: how Saudi Arabia lobbies the US's largest sports bodies|date=2019-09-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-04|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Rappeport|first=Alan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/02/business/economy/saudi-arabia-image-sports.html|title=Saudi Arabia Embraces Western Sports to Rehabilitate Global Image|date=2019-12-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Saudi Arabia}}\n* [[Economy of Saudi Arabia]]\n* [[Mohammad bin Salman]]\n* [[MiSK Foundation]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://vision2030.gov.sa/en/ Official website]\n\n{{Saudi Arabia topics}}\n{{Asia in topic|Economy of}}\n{{World Trade Organization}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Economy Of Saudi Arabia}}\n[[Category:Economic history of Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Economy of Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:2016 in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:2030]]\n[[Category:Projects established in 2016]]\n[[Category:2030 in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Future vision statements of countries]]\n", "text_old": "{{Copy edit|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox government agency\n| agency_name = Saudi Vision 2030\n| nativename = '' \u0631\u0624\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629 2030''\n| type = Development programme\n| seal = \n| logo = Saudi Vision 2030 logo.svg\n| logo_width = 200px\n| logo_caption = The official logo of the project.\n| formed = {{Start date and age|2016|04|25|df=yes}}\n| jurisdiction = [[Government of Saudi Arabia]]\n| minister1_name = [[Mohammad bin Salman]]\n| minister1_pfo = [[Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia]]\n| chief1_name = \n| chief1_position = \n| chief2_name = \n| chief2_position = \n| chief3_name = \n| chief3_position = \n| chief4_name = \n| chief4_position = \n| chief5_name = \n| motto = Saudi Arabia the heart of the Arab and Islamic worlds, the investment powerhouse, and the hub connecting three continents\n| employees = \n| budget = \n| agency_type = Development programme\n| chief5_position = \n| chief6_name = \n| chief6_position = \n| chief7_name = \n| chief7_position = \n| chief8_name = \n| chief8_position = \n| chief9_name = \n| chief9_position = \n| parent_department = \n| keydocument1 = '''Saudi Vision 2030'''\n* [http://vision2030.gov.sa/download/file/fid/417 English]\n* [http://vision2030.gov.sa/download/file/fid/422 Arabic]\n| website = {{URL|http://vision2030.gov.sa/}}\n}}\n{{Politics of Saudi Arabia}}\n\n'''Saudi Vision 2030''' ({{lang-ar|\u0631\u0624\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629 2030}}) is a strategic framework to reduce [[Saudi Arabia]]'s dependence on [[Saudi oil|oil]], diversify its [[economy of Saudi Arabia|economy]], and develop public service sectors such as health, [[education in Saudi Arabia|education]], infrastructure, recreation and [[tourism in Saudi Arabia|tourism]]. Key strategic goals include reinforcing economic and investment activities, increasing non-oil industry trade between countries and to promote a softer and secular image of the Kingdom . It also consists of increasing government spending on the [[Military of Saudi Arabia|military]], manufacturing equipment and ammunition.\n\nThe first details were announced on 25 April 2016 by Crown Prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Marwa Rashad |title=Saudis await Prince's vision of future with hope and concern |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-plan-idUSKCN0XL0B2 |newspaper=Reuters |date=24 April 2016 |access-date= 24 April 2016}}</ref> The Council of Ministers has tasked the [[Council of Economic and Development Affairs (Saudi Arabia)|Council of Economic and Development Affairs]] (CEDA) with identifying and monitoring the mechanisms and measures crucial for the implementation of \"Saudi Arabia\u2019s Vision 2030\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://vision2030.gov.sa/sites/default/files/NTP_En.pdf |title=National Transformation Program 2020 |last= |first= |date= |website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[assassination of Jamal Khashoggi]], it has been said that the expat community is reluctant in investing in Saudi Arabia. In addition to this, assets were moved overseas and the Gulf became unattractive to international businessmen.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/gulf-investment-saudi-arabia-uae-khashoggi-murder-mattew-hedges-mbs-emirates-economy-a8711771.html \u2018People are leaving\u2019: Gulf investors wary after Khashoggi murder and British 'spy' detention], [[Borzou Daragahi]], 9 January 2019, ''[[The Independent]]''</ref> Despite this, foreign investments in the country rose in 2018 by 110% representing double the previous year according to the [[Ministry of Economy and Planning|minister of economy and planning]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-budget-energy-industry-idUKKBN1OI0QU|title=Foreign investment in Saudi Arabia more than doubled in 2018: minister|date=2018-12-19|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-01-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nOil comprises 30-40 percent of the real [[GDP]] of Saudi Arabia, not including the proportion of the economy that is also dependent on the oil distribution. Decreasing this dependence on oil resources has been one of the goals of the government since the 1970s. However, the implementation of this goal has been rather unstable and largely dependent on the prices of oil. The core priority is to be able to develop more alternative sources of revenue for the government, such as taxes, fees and income from the sovereign wealth fund.<ref name=\":0\" /> Another major aspect is to lower the dependency of the citizens of the country on public spending such as spending on subsidies, higher salaries and to increase the portion of the economy contributed by the private sector to provide more employment opportunities and to provide growth in the GDP.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web |url=http://vision2030.gov.sa/sites/default/files/NTP_En.pdf |title=Vision 2030 |last= |first= |date= |website=|access-date=}}</ref> The goals in the Saudi vision 2030 could be compared with other development plans in the Middle East, see for example the [[Kuwait Vision 2035]], [[UAE vision 2021|UAE Vision]] and [[Qatar National Vision 2030]].\n\nThe vision has 3 main pillars: the status of the country as the \"heart of the Arab and Islamic worlds\"; the determination to become a global investment powerhouse; and finally to transform the country's location into a hub connecting the 3 continents (Asia, Europe, Africa).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/perspective/features/2016/04/26/Full-text-of-Saudi-Arabia-s-Vision-2030.html |title=Full-text-of-Saudi-Arabia-s-Vision-2030 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429180619/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/perspective/features/2016/04/26/Full-text-of-Saudi-Arabia-s-Vision-2030.html|archive-date=2016-04-29|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe plan is supervised by a group of people employed under the National Center for Performance Measurement, the Delivery Unit, and the Project Management Office of the Council of Economic and Development Affairs. The National Transformation Program was designed and launched in 2016 across 24 government bodies to enhance the economic and development center.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nSaudi Arabia Vision 2030 lays out targets for diversification and improving competitiveness. It is built around three main themes which set out specific objectives that are to be achieved by the year 2030.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/perspective/features/2016/04/26/Full-text-of-Saudi-Arabia-s-Vision-2030.html |title=Full text of Saudi Arabia\u2019s Vision 2030 |website=english.alarabiya.net |language=en|access-date=2017-12-13}}</ref>\n# A vibrant society: urbanism, culture and entertainment, sports, Umrah, UNESCO heritage sites, life expectancy.\n# A thriving economy: Employment, women in the workforce, international competitiveness, Public Investment Fund, Foreign direct investment, private sector, non-oil exports.\n# An ambitious nation: Non-oil revenues, government effectiveness, and e-government, household savings and income, non-profits and volunteering.\n\n== Projects and initiatives ==\nThe [[Public Investment Fund of Saudi Arabia|PIF]] annually organizes an investment forum, the [[Future Investment Initiative]] or \"Davos in the Desert\" in context of Saudi Vision 2030 in Riyadh. However, amid the rising controversy and escalating tensions due to Saudi's involvement in [[Jamal Khashoggi]]\u2019s disappearance, many companies\u2019 CEOs have backed out of the conference. [[Google Cloud Platform|Google Cloud]], [[KKR & Co. L.P.]], [[Ford Motor Company|Ford Motor]], [[JPMorgan Chase]], [[BlackRock]], [[Uber]] and [[The Blackstone Group]] all withdrew their CEO/Chairman's names from the summit that was held on 23 October 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/finance-ceos-pull-out-of-saudi-davos-in-the-desert-over-khashoggi-risking-lucrative-role-in-kingdoms-economic-reforms/2018/10/15/b10afea4-d0b8-11e8-b2d2-f397227b43f0_story.html?noredirect=on|title=Finance CEOs pull out of Saudi \u2018Davos in the Desert\u2019 over Khashoggi, risking lucrative role in kingdom\u2019s economic reforms|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> Major media houses including [[CNN]], [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]], [[CNBC]], the [[New York Times]], [[Fox Business Network]], the [[Financial Times]], the [[Los Angeles Times]] and [[Huffington Post]] also withdrew as partners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/11/media/saudi-conference-media-sponsors-khashoggi/index.html|title=Media sponsors drop out of Saudi conference after journalist goes missing|publisher=CNN|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== National Transformation Program ===\nOn 7 June 2016, the Saudi Council of Ministers approved the National Transformation Program which sets out the goals and targets to be achieved by the Kingdom by 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/business/economy/2017/05/01/Saudi-Arabia-sets-out-10-programs-to-achieve-the-Vision-2030.html |title=Saudi Arabia sets out 10 programs to achieve Vision 2030 |website=Alarabiya.net |date=1 May 2017 |accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref> It is the first out of three phases each lasting for five years. Each phase will contribute towards achieving a certain number of goals and targets that will eventually help the Kingdom in reaching the ultimate goals of Vision 2030. In addition, to assist the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia to finance all the projects to be developed and facilitate the process of achieving the goals and targets of Vision 2030, Crown Prince Mohammad bin Salman announced, in January 2016, that an [[Initial public offering|IPO]] of [[Saudi Aramco|Saudi ARAMCO]] is going to take place. However, only 5% of the company will be offered on the stock market.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21685529-biggest-oil-all-saudi-arabia-considering-ipo-aramco-probably |title=Saudi Arabia is considering an IPO of Aramco, probably the world\u2019s most valuable company |website=The Economist|access-date=2017-12-13}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Aramco released its financial statements revealing a net income of $111.1 billion in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-aramco-fitch/aramcos-10-billion-plus-bond-plan-shows-profits-put-top-earner-apple-in-shade-idUSKCN1RD15E|title=Aramco's $10 billion-plus bond plan shows profits put top earner Apple in shade|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=31 March 2019}}</ref> In June 2019, [[Financial Times]] reported that Aramco is striving to separate its association with the ministry, ahead of its potential listing. The company has been paying ministry-related expenses, which according to an unnamed person have been kept hidden by Aramco. The report revealed that [[Khalid A. Al-Falih|Khalid Al-Falih]] has been using the company's revenues for his expenses, which are either directly related to Aramco or are diplomatic. However, Falih's ally stated that the chairman's policies have brought in greater revenues for the firm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/96a6fc26-8b92-11e9-a24d-b42f641eca37|title=Saudi Aramco battles oil ministry over use of company funds|publisher=Financial Times|accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Red Sea luxury resort project ===\nA beach resort is proposed to be built on the [[Red Sea]] between the towns of [[Umluj]] and [[Al-Wajh]] in the northern section of the [[Hejaz]]i coast.<ref name = \"resort\">{{cite news |url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1138636/columns |title=Red Sea resort an essential element of Saudi Vision 2030 |date=2 August 2017}}</ref> The resort project will involve, \"50 islands and 34,000 square kilometers in a global upmarket tourism and leisure mega-development\"<ref name = \"resort\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/blog/2017/8/2/bikini-clad-women-in-saudi-arabia-yes-really |title=Bikini-clad women in Saudi Arabia? Yes, really... |date=2 August 2017}}</ref> and will be, \"governed by laws on par with international standards.\" The resort will allow women to wear [[bikinis]] in the pool and beach areas.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2017/08/04/saudi-arabia-allow-women-wear-bikinis-new-beach-resort/538407001/ |title=Saudi Arabia to allow women in bikinis at new beach resort |date=4 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2017/08/05/Women-to-be-allowed-to-wear-bikinis-at-Saudi-Arabia-beach-resort/7121501939370/ |title=Women to be allowed to wear bikinis at Saudi Arabia beach resort |date=5 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe two massive tourism projects along the Red Sea planned by the Saudi government were to be run under the directorship of [[Richard Branson]]. On 11 October 2018, Branson stated that he is suspending his advisory role for the two projects amidst the [[Jamal Khashoggi]] murder.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.virgin.com/richard-branson/my-statement-kingdom-saudi-arabia|title=My Statement on the Kingdom of audi Arabia|accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref> Branson also suspended his talks with the Saudi government about investment in his [[Virgin Galactic]] venture. He said he had \"high hopes for the current government in the Kingdom and its leader Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman\u2026the disappearance of journalist Jamal Khashoggi, if proved true, would clearly change the ability of any of us in the West to do business with the Saudi Government.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2018/oct/11/sir-richard-branson-suspends-saudi-business-talks-over-khashoggi-affair|title=Sir Richard Branson suspends Saudi business talks over Khashoggi affair|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Entertainment sector ===\nIn May 2016, a [[General Authority for Entertainment (Saudi Arabia)|General Authority for Entertainment]] was announced by royal decree, into which over $2 billion have been invested. In Riyadh, the first public live music concert in over 25 years was held in May 2017, which featured American [[country music]]ian [[Toby Keith]] and Saudi singer [[Rabeh Sager]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21722829-puritanical-kingdom-experiments-entertainment-saudi-arabia-allows |title=Saudi Arabia allows concerts\u2014even country music |website=Economist.com |date=1 June 2017 |accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/therecord/2017/05/22/529500923/how-did-toby-keith-get-to-do-a-concert-in-saudi-arabia |title=How Did Toby Keith Get To Do A Concert In Saudi Arabia? |website=Npr.org |date=22 May 2017 |author=Anastasia Tsioulcas |accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref> In April 2017, the government announced a large sports, culture and entertainment complex, of {{convert|334|km2|ha|lk=in}} at Al-Qidiya, south-west of [[Riyadh]]. The project will include a [[Six Flags]] theme park, due to open in 2022.<ref name=\"sixflags\">{{Cite web |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/life-style/travel-and-tourism/2017/04/08/Saudi-Arabia-plans-on-building-its-largest-cultural-sports-and-recreation-city.html |title=Prince Mohammed bin Salman announces Saudi plans for largest entertainment city |website=english.alarabiya.net |language=en|access-date=2017-12-13}}</ref>\n\nAs a component of Vision 2030 there was a celebration of the 87th anniversary of the Saudi founding with concerts and performances, with women for the first time being allowed into the [[King Fahd International Stadium]] in Riyadh.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://zeenews.india.com/world/women-allowed-into-stadium-as-saudi-arabia-promotes-national-pride-part-of-reform-push-2044950.html |title=Women allowed into stadium as Saudi Arabia promotes national pride, part of reform push |date=23 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 5, 2018, the [[General Sports Authority]] announced a 10-year partnership with American [[professional wrestling]] promoter [[WWE|World Wrestling Entertainment]] (WWE) to hold annual [[pay-per-view]] events in Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"GRR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wwe.com/worldwide/article/saudi-arabia-to-host-greatest-royal-rumble-april-2018 |title=Saudi Arabia to host the Greatest Royal Rumble |work=[[WWE]] |author=WWE.com staff |date=March 5, 2018 |accessdate=March 7, 2018}}</ref> The first event, [[Greatest Royal Rumble]], was held 27 April 2018 at [[King Abdullah Sports City]] in [[Jeddah]].<ref name=\"GRR\" /> Due to restrictions on women's rights, WWE's female performers are not featured in these events. An exception to this occurred at [[Crown Jewel (2019)|Crown Jewel]] on 31 October 2019, which featured [[Lacey Evans]] and [[Natalya Neidhart|Natalya]] in the first women's professional wrestling match to be held in Saudi Arabia. In observation of conservative dress, they both wore black leggings and T-shirts over bodysuits instead of their normal ring attire.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://mirrorherald.com/crown-jewel-in-saudi-hosted-women-players-for-first-time/|title=Reforms Under Veil: Saudi\u2019s First Women Wrestling Battled in Bodysuits|accessdate=1 February 2020|website=Mirror Herald}}</ref>\n\nSaudi Arabia lifted its 35-year moratorium on the construction of new [[movie theater]]s in the country, with the first (under the ownership of [[AMC Theatres]]) opened on 18 April 2018 in [[Riyadh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/04/18/media/saudi-arabia-movies-black-panther-amc/index.html|title='Black Panther' comes to Saudi Arabia as movie theater ban ends|last1=Petroff|first1=Alanna|date=18 April 2018|website=CNN.com|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/amc-proceeding-plan-build-movie-theaters-saudi-arabia-1199362|title=AMC Proceeding With Plan to Build Movie Theaters in Saudi Arabia|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, the MDL Beast [[music festival]] was held in Riyadh, attracting 200,000 visitors over three days, and featuring acts such as [[Afrojack]], [[David Guetta]], [[Monsta X]] [[R3hab]], and [[J Balvin]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/music/i-don-t-have-to-leave-saudi-for-fun-anymore-mdl-beast-represents-a-paradigm-shift-in-the-kingdom-1.954878|title='I don't have to leave Saudi for fun anymore': MDL Beast represents a 'paradigm shift' in the kingdom|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Saudi Arabia unveiled its plans to build a new racing circuit in [[Al-Qiddiya|Qiddiya]], designed by former [[Formula One]] driver [[Alexander Wurz]], with a goal for it to host F1 or [[MotoGP]] events as early as 2023.<ref name=\"BBCJan20\">{{cite news|author=Andrew Benson|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/51137520|title=Formula 1: Saudi Arabia unveils plans for race in 2023|date=17 January 2020|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Women's rights ===\nIn January 2013, women were announced as members of the nation's [[Consultative Assembly of Saudi Arabia|Consultative Assembly]]. In 2015, they were allowed to run for office in municipal elections.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2013/01/11/saudi-king-grants-women-seats-on-advisory-council-for-1st-time.html |title=Saudi king grants women seats on advisory council for 1st time |website=Foxnews.com |date=11 January 2013 |accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2017, Saudi state schools announced offering physical education classes to both boys and girls starting in the fall of 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/07/13/saudi-arabia-state-schools-allow-girls-sports |title=Saudi Arabia: State Schools to Allow Girls\u2019 Sports |website=Hrw.org |date=13 July 2017 |accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref> Later that same year, the state announced allowing men and women to attend sports events, including inside sports stadiums.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/30/saudi-arabia-to-allow-women-into-sports-stadiums-as-reform-push-intensifies |title=Saudi Arabia to allow women into sports stadiums as reform push intensifies |website=Theguardian.com |date=30 October 2017 |accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref> On September 26, 2017, a royal decree granted women the right to drive vehicles, a move which would take effect in June 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/26/world/middleeast/saudi-arabia-women-drive.html |title=Saudi Arabia Agrees to Let Women Drive |website=Nytimes.com |date=26 September 2017 |author=Ben Hubbard |accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhile a few relaxations were suggested and implemented by the government for the welfare of women, more progress still needs to be made. As many women activists have been held and criminalized since 2015, without allowing access to a lawyer. The case of [[Israa al-Ghomgham]] came into light after she and her husband were arrested in December 2015 for calling the release of political prisoners and an end to anti-Shia government discrimination.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/saudi-arabia-israa-alghomgham-execution-womens-rights-political-activist-qatif-a8501411.html|title=Saudi Arabia plans to execute first female political activist|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref> Saudi prosecutors are seeking death penalty for Ghomgham.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/aug/22/saudi-arabia-seeks-its-first-death-penalty-against-a-female-human-rights-activist|title=Saudi Arabia seeks death penalty against female human rights activist|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the government based web application [[Absher (application)|Absher]] gained media attention and was criticized for tracking the movement of the women of the kingdom. The app, which promotes a male guardianship system, allows men to manage women's lives digitally by specifying when and from where a woman can travel. The app also sends alerts to men's phones in case a woman uses her passport at the border.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisisinsider.com/absher-saudi-website-men-control-women-stop-escape-2019-1|title=Saudi Arabia runs a huge, sinister online database of women that men use to track them and stop them from running away|publisher=The Insider|accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref> The European Parliament, US Senator and US Representatives condemned the app and urged the kingdom to abolish its male guardianship system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-eu-saudi-women/eu-lawmakers-urge-saudi-arabia-to-end-womens-guardianship-system-idUKKCN1Q327T|title=EU lawmakers urge Saudi Arabia to end women's guardianship system|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisisinsider.com/absher-saudi-arabia-defends-app-investigated-by-apple-google-2019-2|title=Saudi Arabia tried to justify its app that lets men control where women travel amid a firestorm of criticism| publisher=The Insider|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Tourism Visa ===\nIn compliance with Saudi vision 2030, Saudi Arabia formally announced on 27 September 2019 the issuance of the tourist visa allowing visitors from 49 countries to visit the country up to 90 days for a fee of $80. The visa can be either obtained online (eVisa) or on arrival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.visitsaudi.com/en/about-evisa.html|title=Welcome to Arabia - About the Tourism Visa |last=|first= |date= |website=visitsaudi.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Other projects ===\nSome of the other major projects to be developed are listed in the table below:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Some of the projects to be developed as a part of Vision 2030\n!Project Name\n!Location\n!Total Area (km\u00b2)\n!Date of Announcement\n!Expected Finish Date\n!Cost\n|-\n!New Taif Project<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/518430/SAUDI-ARABIA/Taif-projects |title=King inaugurates SR11bn New Taif projects |date=2017-10-01 |work=Saudigazette|access-date=2017-12-13 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n|[[Taif]]\n|1250\n|1 March 2017\n|2020\n|3 Billion Dollars\n|-\n!Diriyah Gate Project<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1421416/saudi-arabia|title=Ad Diriyah a \u2018jewel\u2019 of Saudi Arabia, its revival key to Kingdom\u2019s future, says project chief|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n| [[Diriyah]]\n| 1.5\n|20 July 2017\n|2030\n|Unknown\n|-\n![[Al-Qiddiya|Al-Qiddiya Project]]<ref name=\"sixflags\"/>\n|Al-Qiddiya, south-west of [[Riyadh]]\n|334\n|8 April 2017\n|2022\n|2.7 Billion Dollars\n|-\n!Al-Faisaliah project<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.argaam.com/en/article/articledetail/id/497359 |title=Al-Faisaliah project to be finalized by 2050, says Makkah governor |date=26 July 2017 |work=Argaam.com|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1165351/saudi-arabia|title=Makkah\u2019s Al-Faisaliah project to be unveiled at Jeddah property show|date=22 September 2017|website=Arab News|language=en-US|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref> \n|West of [[Makkah]] \n|2,450 \n|26 July 2017\n|First Phase will be completed by the end of 2020\n|Unknown\n|-\n!Downtown Jeddah<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-09-27/saudi-fund-to-develop-jeddah-downtown-with-4-8-billion-project |title=Saudi Fund to Develop Jeddah Downtown With $4.8 Billion Project |work=Bloomberg.com |access-date=2017-12-13 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005075051/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-09-27/saudi-fund-to-develop-jeddah-downtown-with-4-8-billion-project |archivedate=2017-10-05 }}</ref>\n|[[Jeddah]]\n|5.2\n|27 September 2017\n|First phase will be completed by the end of 2022\n|4.8 Billion Dollars\n|-\n![[NEOM]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-24/saudi-arabia-to-build-new-mega-city-on-country-s-north-coast |title=Saudi Arabia Just Announced Plans to Build a Mega City That Will Cost $500 Billion |date=2017-10-24 |work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2017-12-13}}</ref>\n|Northwest of Saudi Arabia \n|26,500\n|24 October 2017\n|First Phase will be completed by the end of 2025\n|500 Billion Dollars\n|-\n!The Renewable Energy Project<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-softbank-group-solar/softbank-says-it-is-working-with-saudi-pif-on-solar-power-project-idUSKCN1MC28T|title=Softbank says it is working with Saudi PIF on solar power project|website=Reuters.com|language=en|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n| Multiple Locations\n| Unknown\n|27 March 2018\n|2030\n|200 Billion\n|-\n![[Amaala|Amaala Project]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimdobson/2018/12/26/saudi-arabia-unveils-plans-to-create-massive-red-sea-wellness-destinations/#3b97aa55dfb6 |title=Saudi Arabia Unveils Plans To Create Massive Red Sea Wellness Destinations |date=26 December 2018 |work=Forbes.com|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n|Along the [[Red Sea]] \n|3,800\n|26 September 2018\n|First Phase will be completed by the end of 2020\n|Unknown\n|-\n![[King Salman Energy Park]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saudiaramco.com:443/en/News-Media/News/2018/King%20Salman%20Energy%20Park|title=King Salman Energy Park: Saudi Aramco builds a sustainable global energy hub from the ground up - Saudi Aramco|website=saudiaramco.com|language=en|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n|Between [[Dammam]] and [[Al-Ahsa Governorate|Al-Ahsa]]\n|50\n|5 December 2018\n|First Phase will be completed by the end of 2021\n|1.6 Billion\n|-\n![[Al-`Ula#Al-Ula vision|Al-Ula Vision]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cic.org.sa/2019/02/royal-commission-for-alula-hosts-launching-the-vision-for-alula/|title=Royal Commission for AlUla hosts \u2018Launching the Vision for AlUla\u2019|website=The Saudi Center for International Communication|language=en|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/558885/SAUDI-ARABIA/Al-Ula-Vision-KSA-gift-to-world|title='Al Ula Vision... Saudi Arabia gift to world'|date=2019-02-11|website=Saudigazette|language=English|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref>\n| [[Al-`Ula]]\n| 22500\n|11 February 2019\n|2030\n|Unknown\n|-\n![[King Salman Park]], Sports Boulevard, Green Riyadh and Riyadh Art<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saudiaramco.com:443/en/News-Media/News/2018/King%20Salman%20Energy%20Park|title=King Salman Launches $23 Bln Wellbeing Projects in Riyadh|website=Asharq Al-Awsat|language=en|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saudiaramco.com:443/en/News-Media/News/2018/King%20Salman%20Energy%20Park|title=King Salman Announces $23 Billion for Four Entertainment Projects Including the \u2018World\u2019s Biggest Park\u2019 in Riyadh|website=Saudi-US Trade Group|language=en|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n| [[Riyadh]]\n| +149\n|19 March 2019\n|Unknown\n|23 Billion\n|-\n![[Great Mosque of Mecca]]<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/528131|title=Expansion and redevelopment define Saudi Arabia construction|date=2018-02-11|website=Saudigazette|language=English|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n|[[Mecca]]\n|250,000 \n|2017\n|mid-2018\n|21.3 Billion Dollars\n|-\n!Mall of Saudi<ref name=\":3\" />\n|[[Riyadh]]\n|8666,000\n|2017\n|2022\n|3.2 Billion Dollars\n|-\n!New Jeddah Downtown \u2013 Phase 1<ref name=\":3\" />\n|[[Jeddah]]\n|unknown\n|2017\n|unknown\n|2 Billion Dollars\n|-\n|}\n\n== Implementation ==\n=== Vision Realization Programs ===\nTo achieve the strategic goals and targets of vision 2030, thirteen programs called Vision Realization Programs (VRPs) were established. The VRPs were presented by [[Council of Economic and Development Affairs (Saudi Arabia)|Council of Economic and Development Affairs]] (CEDA) on Monday 24 April 2017. The VRPs are as follows:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vision2030.gov.sa/en/programs|title=Programs {{!}} Saudi Vision 2030|website=vision2030.gov.sa|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref>\n\n#[[Quality of Life Program 2020|Quality of Life Program]].\n# Financial Sector Development Program.\n# Housing Program.\n# Fiscal Balance Program.\n#[[National Transformation Program 2020 (Saudi Arabia)|National Transformation Program]].\n#[[Public Investment Fund of Saudi Arabia|Public Investment Fund Program]].\n# Privatization Program.\n# National Companies Promotion Program.\n# National Industrial Development and Logistics Program.\n# Strategic Partnerships Program.\n# Hajj and Umrah Program.\n# Human Capital Development Program.\n# Saudi Character Enrichment Program.\n\n=== Supervision ===\nThe plan is supervised by Crown Prince Mohammad bin Salman. Three levels ensure the application of the plan:\n* Overall, Vision 2030's directions and decision-making roles lie within a Council of Ministers and a [[Council of Economic and Development Affairs (Saudi Arabia)|Council of Economic and Development Affairs]] (CEDA).\n* CEDA's director, as well as the managers of the first 12 Vision Realization Programs, ensure the following-up of the plan on the five-year level.\n* Annually, each entity concerned in the 2030 Vision is individually responsible for its budget and objectives.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n=== Government entities reconstruction ===\nTo achieve the strategic objectives of Vision 2030, new government entities were created and existing entities were reconstructed and/or merged.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vision2030.gov.sa/download/file/fid/1319|title=KSA Vision 2030 Strategic Objectives and Vision Realization Programs|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! New entity\n! Reconstructed and/or merged from previous entity\n! Previous entity\n|-\n|[[Council of Economic and Development Affairs (Saudi Arabia)|Council of Economic and Development Affairs]] (CEDA) PMO\n| No\n| \n|-\n|Delivery Unit (DU)\n| No\n|\n|-\n|National Center for Performance Management (Adaa)\n| No\n|\n|-\n|Corporate Communication Unit at CEDA (CCU) \n| No\n|\n|-\n|General Authority for Culture (GAC)\n| No\n|\n|-\n|[[General Authority for Entertainment (Saudi Arabia)|General Authority for Entertainment]] of (GEA)\n| No\n|\n|-\n|Strategic Management Committee and Strategic Management Office (SMO)\n| No\n|\n|-\n|[[Ministry of Commerce and Investment (Saudi Arabia)|Ministry of Commerce and Investment]]\n| Yes\n|Ministry of Commerce and Industry\n|-\n|Ministry of Labor Ministry of Labor and Social Development\n| Yes\n|Ministry of Social Affairs\n|-\n|Ministry of Energy, Industry and Mineral Resources\n| Yes\n|Ministry of Petroleum and Mineral Resources and\n|-\n|Ministry of Environment, Water and Agriculture\n|\n|Ministry of Water and Electricity and Ministry of Agriculture\n|-\n|[[Ministry of Hajj and Umrah]]\n| Yes\n|Ministry of [[Hajj]]\n|-\n|Public Education Evaluation Commission\n| Yes\n|Education Evaluation Commission\n|}\n\n== Critical reactions ==\nThe [[IMF]]'s country report on Saudi Arabia, launched a few months following the announcement of Vision 2030, explained that the fiscal deficit in the Saudi economy would indeed continue to narrow in 2016. It also claimed that recent, major government deposits at the [[Saudi Arabian Monetary Authority]] (SAMA) acted as policy buffers to smooth the transition that the plan is leading.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/scr/2016/cr16326.pdf |title=IMF Country Report No. 16/326 |website=Imf.org |date=October 2016 |accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref> In 2016 the IMF publicly warned that Saudi Arabia risks having no more foreign reserve currency within a 5-year period.<ref name=\"ody\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theodysseyonline.com/saudi-arabias-vision-2030-is-going-to-fail |title=Saudi Arabia\u2019s Vision 2030 Is Going To Fail |website=Theodysseyonline.com |date=16 May 2016 |author=Ian Leclecr |accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref> In 2017, it projected that SAMA's net foreign assets would continue to decline, though remaining at a \"comfortable level\". It expects that the fiscal deficit will continue to improve over the coming years, also noting that non-performing loans remained low, despite a slight increase to 1.4 percent in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imf.org/en/News/Articles/2017/07/21/pr17292-imf-executive-board-concludes-2017-article-iv-consultation-with-saudi-arabia |title=IMF Executive Board Concludes 2017 Article IV Consultation with Saudi Arabia |website=Imf.org |date=21 July 2017 |accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nOver 300 specific targets have been announced across 25 government entities via the National Transformation Plan document to reach these objectives by 2020. The National Transformation Plan brings over 150 expected initial public offerings. However, reports noted the \"key person dependency\" of the Vision and the NTP, with regards to Crown Prince Mohammad bin Salman.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gib.com/sites/default/files/ntp_ebook_-_final_12_-_low-res_0_0.pdf |title=Assessment of the National Transformation Program (NTP) |website=Gib.com |date=2016 |accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref> Other criticisms have been regarding the lack of information about the detailed plans to accompany the intended transformation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.bath.ac.uk/iprblog/2017/08/10/the-uncertain-vision-saudi-arabia-and-vision-2030/ |title=Looking to the Future: Saudi Arabia and Vision 2030 |website=Bath.ac.uk |date=10 August 2017 |accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nCertain journalists speculated that the plan's goals were overly ambitious, and noted that non-oil growth so far was insufficient and would threaten the plan's successful implementation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oilprice.com/Energy/Energy-General/How-Realistic-Is-Saudi-Arabias-2-Trillion-Sovereign-Wealth-Fund.html |title=How Realistic Is Saudi Arabia\u2019s $2 Trillion Sovereign Wealth Fund? |website=Oilprice.com |date=7 April 2017 |author=Rakesh Upadhyay |accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-01/saudi-non-oil-growth-is-stagnating-even-with-2030-vision-chart |title=Saudi Non-Oil Growth Is Stagnating Even With 2030 Vision: Chart |website=Bloomberg.com |date=1 October 2017 |author=Vivian Nereim |accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref> One report felt that despite the national plan's overall forward-thinking direction, \"political reform appears to be absent from the policy agenda\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chathamhouse.org/sites/files/chathamhouse/publications/research/2017-07-20-vision-2030-saudi-kinninmont.pdf |title=Vision 2030 and Saudi Arabia\u2019s Social Contract |website=Chathamhouse.org |date=July 2017 |author=Jane Kinninmont |accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nReactions were mixed following the announcement that Saudi Arabia would lift the driving ban on women.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/09/saudi-women-driving-ban-lifted-euphoria-sarcasm-170927053659253.html |title=Saudi women driving ban lifted: Euphoria and sarcasm |website=Aljazeera.com |date=27 September 2017 |accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref> Similarly to the overarching Vision 2030, some understood the announcement via royal decree as a reaction to outside pressure, while others applauded the move.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/posteverything/wp/2017/09/28/yes-letting-women-in-saudi-arabia-drive-is-a-baby-step-but-we-shouldnt-laugh-at-it/ |title=Yes, letting women in Saudi Arabia drive is a baby step. But we shouldn\u2019t laugh at it |website=Washinpost.com |date=28 September 2017 |author=Eman Quotah |accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a research paper written by Jane Kinninmont for the Middle East and North Africa Programme, from the structural disadvantages of the country such as weak institutions, inefficient bureaucracy and significant gaps between the labor force required by the labor market and the current educational system hinder some of the growth prospects of the country. Rebalancing the job market in the private sector will also prove to be a challenge since it is currently majority staffed by expatriates. One of the difficulties is that the private sector has lower paying salaries and expats are easier to hire and fire. Currently twice as many Saudi nationals work in the public sector than in the private sector. The challenge lies in getting a larger portion of the nationals to accept lower paying jobs that could require higher working hours than that of the public sector. Another aspect to be considered is moving the private sector away from the business activities that require very low-cost labor.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.chathamhouse.org/sites/files/chathamhouse/publications/research/2017-07-20-vision-2030-saudi-kinninmont.pdf |title=Vision 2030 and Saudi Arabia\u2019s Social Contract Austerity and Transformation |last= |first= |date= |website=Chathamhouse|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Hilal Khashan from the American conservative think tank [[Middle East Forum]], to have the 2030 plan succeed ignoring the relationship between economic and political development is no longer a viable option, the developments required to increase the GDP as planned will encourage the breakage of the tribal system taking place. Another aspect is the \"zero tolerance to corruption\" that may be very difficult to achieve with a \"society where family, tribal, and regional ties are stronger than the nebulous conception of state identity\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal |last=Khashan |first=Hilal |date=2017-01-01 |title=Saudi Arabia's Flawed \"Vision 2030\" |url=http://www.meforum.org/6397/saudi-arabia-flawed-vision-2030 |journal=Middle East Quarterly |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe hosting of sporting events in Saudi Arabia under the strategy have been described as attempts to [[Sportswashing|sportswash]] the country's human rights record.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Zidan|first=Karim|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/sep/02/sportswashing-saudi-arabia-sports-mohammed-bin-salman|title=Sportswashing: how Saudi Arabia lobbies the US's largest sports bodies|date=2019-09-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-04|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Rappeport|first=Alan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/02/business/economy/saudi-arabia-image-sports.html|title=Saudi Arabia Embraces Western Sports to Rehabilitate Global Image|date=2019-12-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Saudi Arabia}}\n* [[Economy of Saudi Arabia]]\n* [[Mohammad bin Salman]]\n* [[MiSK Foundation]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://vision2030.gov.sa/en/ Official website]\n\n{{Saudi Arabia topics}}\n{{Asia in topic|Economy of}}\n{{World Trade Organization}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Economy Of Saudi Arabia}}\n[[Category:Economic history of Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Economy of Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:2016 in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:2030]]\n[[Category:Projects established in 2016]]\n[[Category:2030 in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Future vision statements of countries]]\n", "name_user": "51.252.86.251", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saudi_Vision_2030"}
{"title_page": "Central West (New South Wales)", "text_new": "{{morefootnotes|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type     = region    <!-- This box may still be removed if it is objected to -->\n| name     = Central West\n| state    = nsw\n| image    = LachlanAtCowra.JPG\n| caption  = <small>The Lachlan River at [[Cowra, New South Wales|Cowra]]</small>\n| coordinates = \n| lga      = [[Bathurst Region]], [[Orange City (New South Wales)|Orange City]], [[Cowra Shire]], [[Parkes Shire]], [[Lithgow City]], [[Oberon Shire]], [[Mid-Western Regional Council]], [[Forbes Shire]], [[Cabonne Shire]], [[Weddin Shire]], [[Bland Shire]], [[Lachlan Shire]]\n| pop      = 209,810\n| pop_year = 30 June 2016\n| pop_footnotes = <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/allprimarymainfeatures/797F86DBD192B8F8CA2568A9001393CD?opendocument# |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305015843/http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/allprimarymainfeatures/797F86DBD192B8F8CA2568A9001393CD?opendocument# |archive-date=5 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| stategov = [[Electoral district of Bathurst|Bathurst]]\n| stategov2 = [[Electoral district of Cootamundra|Cootamundra]]\n| stategov3 = [[Electoral district of Dubbo|Dubbo]]\n| stategov4 = [[Electoral district of Orange|Orange]] \n| fedgov   = [[Division of Calare|Calare]]\n| near-nw      = [[Orana (New South Wales)|Orana]]\n| near-n       = [[Hunter Region|Upper Hunter]]\n| near-ne      = [[Hunter Region|Hunter]]\n| near-w       = [[Orana (New South Wales)|Orana]]\n| near-e       = [[Greater Blue Mountains Area]]\n| near-sw      = [[South West Slopes]]\n| near-s       = [[South West Slopes]]\n| near-se      = [[Southern Tablelands]]\n}}\n\n'''The Central West''' is a region of [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]]. The region is geographically in eastern New South Wales, in the area west of the [[Blue Mountains (Australia)|Blue Mountains]], which are west of [[Sydney]]. It has an area of {{convert|63262|km2}}.<ref name=\"BusinessNSW\">[http://www.business.nsw.gov.au/region/profiles/Central%20West.htm Central West Region - the agricultural heart of New South Wales] website of New South Wales Department of State and Regional Development, accessed 12 November 2006</ref> The region includes the area meteorologically defined as the [[Central Tablelands]], located in the eastern part of the region.\n\nMajor population and service centres in the Central West include the cities of [[Bathurst, New South Wales|Bathurst]] and [[Orange, New South Wales|Orange]]; and the large towns of [[Lithgow, New South Wales|Lithgow]], [[Cowra, New South Wales|Cowra]], [[Mudgee]] and [[Parkes, New South Wales|Parkes]]. Bathurst and Orange are home to campuses of [[Charles Sturt University]], and Lithgow housing the [[University of Notre Dame Australia|University of Notre Dame Regional Clinical School]].\n\n== Cities and towns ==\nThe Central West includes two cities: [[Bathurst, New South Wales|Bathurst]] and [[Orange, New South Wales|Orange]]; four large towns: [[Cowra, New South Wales|Cowra]], [[Mudgee]], [[Parkes, New South Wales|Parkes]] and [[Lithgow, New South Wales|Lithgow]]; smaller centres, such as [[Oberon, New South Wales|Oberon]] and [[Forbes, New South Wales|Forbes]]; and small towns and villages such as [[Canowindra, New South Wales|Canowindra]], [[Cudal, New South Wales|Cudal]], [[Molong, New South Wales|Molong]], [[Grenfell, New South Wales|Grenfell]], [[West Wyalong, New South Wales|West Wyalong]], [[Portland, New South Wales|Portland]], [[Wallerawang]], [[Condobolin, New South Wales|Condobolin]] and [[Eugowra, New South Wales|Eugowra]].\n\n===Demography and area===\nThe following [[Local government areas of New South Wales|local government areas]] are contained within the region:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|+Population by Local Government Area\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Central West rank\n! scope=\"col\" | Local Government Area\n! scope=\"col\" | Population 30 June  2016<ref name=\"3218.0\">{{cite web |publisher=Australian Bureau of Statistics |title=3218.0 \u2013 Regional Population Growth, Australia, 2016 |url=http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/allprimarymainfeatures/797F86DBD192B8F8CA2568A9001393CD?opendocument |access-date=9 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305015843/http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/allprimarymainfeatures/797F86DBD192B8F8CA2568A9001393CD?opendocument# |archive-date=5 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" | 10 year growth rate\n! scope=\"col\" | Population density (people/km<sup>2</sup>)\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 1\n| [[Bathurst Regional Council]]\n| 42,389\n| 14.8\n| 11.1\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 2\n| [[City of Orange (New South Wales)|Orange City]]\n| 41,384\n| 13.8\n| 145.6\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 3\n| [[Mid-Western Regional Council]]\n| 24,569\n| 13.5\n| 2.8\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 4\n| [[City of Lithgow|City of Lithgow Council]]\n| 21,524\n| 6.6\n| 4.8\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 7\n| [[Parkes Shire|Parkes Shire Council]]\n| 14,946\n| 2.4\n| 2.5\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 8\n| [[Cabonne Shire Council|Cabonne Shire]]\n| 13,625\n| 7.8\n| 2.3\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 9\n| [[Cowra Shire Council|Cowra Shire]]\n| 12,673\n| -0.6\n| 4.5\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 10\n| [[Forbes Shire Council|Forbes Shire]]\n| 9,808\n| 2.8\n| 2.1\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 11\n| [[Blayney Shire Council|Blayney Shire]]\n| 7,418\n| 10.0\n| 4.9\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 12\n| [[Lachlan Shire Council|Lachlan Shire]]\n| 6,352\n| -7.0\n| 0.4\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 13\n| [[Bland Shire Council|Bland Shire]]\n| 6,031\n| -2.9\n| 0.7\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 14\n| [[Oberon Council|Oberon Shire]]\n| 5,399\n| 4.2\n| 1.5\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 15\n| [[Weddin Shire Council|Weddin Shire]]\n| 3,692\n| -0.8\n| 1.1\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Central West\n! style=\"text-align:right\" | 209,810\n! style=\"text-align:right\" | 8.5\n! style=\"text-align:right\" | 3.0\n|}\n\n== Terrain ==\nThe Central West's east is higher, wetter and hillier and supports orchards, [[vineyard]]s, vegetable-growing and pastoralism. The west is flatter and drier and supports grain crops and pastoralism.\n\n== Major highways ==\nThe Central West region is traversed by the [[Great Western Highway]], the [[Mid-Western Highway]], the [[Mitchell Highway]], the [[Newell Highway]] and the [[Castlereagh Highway]].\n\n== Media ==\nThe Central West has several radio stations, including 97.9 2LVR (a community radio station), 105.1 [[2GZ|2GZFM]], 105.9 [[Star FM]], 107.9 [[Move FM]], 107.5 Community Radio, 103.5 [[Rhema FM]] and [[2EL|1089AM]] \u2014 a commercial station that gets most of its programming from [[2SM]] in Sydney. Other electronic media are represented by the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] with both television and radio broadcasting; and by television stations [[Prime7]], [[WIN Television|WIN]], and [[Southern Cross Nine]].\n\nTwo major newspapers are published in the region, the ''[[Central Western Daily]]'' newspaper is published in Orange and the [[The Western Advocate (Bathurst, New South Wales)|Western Advocate]] in Bathurst. Numerous other local papers serve the remaining large towns.\n\n== History ==\nThe Central West area was originally inhabited by the Wiradjuri people. The first white explorer, George Wilson Evans, entered the [[Wyangala#Water resources|Lachlan Valley]] in 1815. He named the area the Oxley Plains after his superior the surveyor-general, John Oxley. In 1817 he deemed the area unfit for white settlement. A Military Depot was established not long after at Soldiers Flat near present-day Billimari. Arthur Ranken and James Sloan, from Bathurst, were amongst the first white settlers on the Lachlan. They moved to the area in 1831.\n\nIn the 1850s many gold prospectors passed through headed for gold fields at Lambing Flat ([[Young, New South Wales|Young]]) and [[Grenfell, New South Wales|Grenfell]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Central West (New South Wales)}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091112022439/http://www.bom.gov.au/weather/nsw/nsw-forecast-map.shtml NSW Forecast Areas map]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080905131130/http://www.dlg.nsw.gov.au/dlg/dlghome/dlg_regions.asp?mi=0&ml=8&regiontype=1&region=CW Department of Local Government page for the region] listing links to council pages\n* [http://www.dmoz.org/Regional/Oceania/Australia/New_South_Wales/Regions/Central_West/ \"Open Directory\" listing]\n\n{{Regions of New South Wales |state=autocollapse}}\n\n[[Category:Regions of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Central West (New South Wales)| ]]\n[[Category:Newell Highway]]\n", "text_old": "{{morefootnotes|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type     = region    <!-- This box may still be removed if it is objected to -->\n| name     = Central West\n| state    = nsw\n| image    = LachlanAtCowra.JPG\n| caption  = <small>The Lachlan River at [[Cowra, New South Wales|Cowra]]</small>\n| coordinates = \n| lga      = [[Bathurst Region]], [[Orange City (New South Wales)|City of Orange]], [[Cowra Shire]], [[Parkes Shire]], [[Lithgow City]], [[Oberon Shire]], [[Mid-Western Regional Council]], [[Forbes Shire]], [[Cabonne Shire]], [[Weddin Shire]], [[Bland Shire]], [[Lachlan Shire]]\n| pop      = 209,810\n| pop_year = 30 June 2016\n| pop_footnotes = <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/allprimarymainfeatures/797F86DBD192B8F8CA2568A9001393CD?opendocument# |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305015843/http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/allprimarymainfeatures/797F86DBD192B8F8CA2568A9001393CD?opendocument# |archive-date=5 March 2016 |url